            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.VII.R14</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Bleeding Heart Yard &amp; foreigners [...]</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-837a00a8-7fff-2232-9c8e-350c4460d17e\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Dickens will expound at length on &ldquo;the Bleeding Hearts&rdquo; and their objection to foreigners on the grounds of various stereotypes and generalizations (LD 295-96). This passage is used to contrast their general view on the subject with their appreciation of the &ldquo;good-humoured&rdquo; Cavalletto. The phrase &ldquo;Mrs. Plornish as Interpreter&rdquo; appears as written and refers to the amusing way in which she attempts to rephrase Cavalletto&rsquo;s words (296).</p>"
